# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-load-balancing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] The term "failover", although probably in use by engineers much earlier, can be found in a 1962 declassified NASA report.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] The term "switchover" can be found in the 1950s when describing '"Hot" and "Cold" Standby Systems', with the current meaning of immediate switchover to a running system (hot) and delayed switchover to a system that needs starting (cold).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] A conference proceedings from 1957 describes computer systems with both Emergency Switchover (i.e., failover) and Scheduled Failover (for maintenance).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] Systems designers usually provide failover capability in servers, systems or networks requiring high availability and a high degree of reliability.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] At the server level, failover automation usually sends a heartbeat between two servers, either through the network or through a separate connection (for example, RS-232).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] In the most common design, as long as a regular "pulse" or heartbeat continues between the main server and the second server, the second server will not bring its systems online; however, a few systems actively use all servers and can failover their work to remaining servers after a failure.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] There may also be a third "spare parts" server that has running spare components for "hot" switching to prevent downtime.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] The second server takes over the work of the first as soon as it detects an alteration in the heartbeat of the first machine.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] Some systems have the ability to send a notification of failover.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] Certain systems, intentionally, do not fail over entirely automatically, but require human intervention.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] This "automated with manual approval" configuration runs automatically once a human has approved the failover.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] The use of virtualization software has allowed failover practices to become less reliant on physical hardware through the process referred to as migration in which a running virtual machine is moved from one physical host to another, with little or no disruption in service.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] Failover and failback technology are also regularly used in the Microsoft SQL Server database, in which SQL Server Failover Cluster Instance (FCI) is installed and configured on top of the Windows Server Failover Cluster (WSFC).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] The SQL Server groups and resources running on WSFC can be manually failed over to the second node for any planned maintenance on the first node or automatically fail over to the second node in case of any issues on the first node.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/failover] In the same way, a failback operation can be performed to the first node once the issue is resolved or maintenance is done on it.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] The name of the algorithm comes from the round-robin principle known from other fields, where each person takes an equal share of something in turn.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] To schedule processes fairly, a round-robin scheduler generally employs time-sharing, giving each job a time slot or *quantum* (its allowance of CPU time), and interrupting the job if it is not completed by then.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] The job is resumed next time a time slot is assigned to that process.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] If the process terminates or changes its state to waiting during its attributed time quantum, the scheduler selects the first process in the ready queue to execute.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] In the absence of time-sharing, or if the quanta were large relative to the sizes of the jobs, a process that produced large jobs would be favored over other processes.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Round-robin algorithm is a pre-emptive algorithm as the scheduler forces the process out of the CPU once the time quota expires.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] For example, if the time slot is 100 milliseconds, and *job1* takes a total time of 250 ms to complete, the round-robin scheduler will suspend the job after 100 ms and give other jobs their time on the CPU.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Once the other jobs have had their equal share (100 ms each), *job1* will get another allocation of CPU time and the cycle will repeat.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] This process continues until the job finishes and needs no more time on the CPU.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Third allocation = 100 ms but *job1* self-terminates after 50 ms.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Another approach is to divide all processes into an equal number of timing quanta such that the quantum size is proportional to the size of the process.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Hence, all processes end at the same time.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] In best-effort packet switching and other statistical multiplexing, round-robin scheduling can be used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] A multiplexer, switch, or router that provides round-robin scheduling has a separate queue for every data flow, where a data flow may be identified by its source and destination address.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] The algorithm allows every active data flow that has data packets in the queue to take turns in transferring packets on a shared channel in a periodically repeated order.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] The scheduling is work-conserving, meaning that if one flow is out of packets, the next data flow will take its place.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Hence, the scheduling tries to prevent link resources from going unused.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Round-robin scheduling results in max-min fairness if the data packets are equally sized, since the data flow that has waited the longest time is given scheduling priority.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] It may not be desirable if the size of the data packets varies widely from one job to another.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] A user that produces large packets would be favored over other users.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] In that case fair queuing would be preferable.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] If guaranteed or differentiated quality of service is offered, and not only best-effort communication, deficit round-robin (DRR) scheduling, weighted round-robin (WRR) scheduling, or weighted fair queuing (WFQ) may be considered.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] In multiple-access networks, where several terminals are connected to a shared physical medium, round-robin scheduling may be provided by token passing channel access schemes such as Token Ring, or by polling or resource reservation from a central control station.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] In a centralized wireless packet radio network, where many stations share one frequency channel, a scheduling algorithm in a central base station may reserve time slots for the mobile stations in a round-robin fashion and provide fairness.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] However, if link adaptation is used, it will take a much longer time to transmit a certain amount of data to "expensive" users than to others since the channel conditions differ.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] It would be more efficient to wait with the transmission until the channel conditions are improved, or at least to give scheduling priority to less expensive users.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Round-robin scheduling does not utilize this.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Higher throughput and system spectrum efficiency may be achieved by channel-dependent scheduling, for example a proportionally fair algorithm, or maximum throughput scheduling.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] Note that the latter is characterized by undesirable scheduling starvation.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/round-robin-scheduling] This type of scheduling is one of the very basic algorithms for Operating Systems in computers which can be implemented through a circular queue data structure.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] A **server farm** or **server cluster** is a collection of computer servers, usually maintained by an organization to supply server functionality far beyond the capability of a single machine.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] They often consist of thousands of computers which require a large amount of power to run and to keep cool.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] At the optimum performance level, a server farm has enormous financial and environmental costs.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] They often include backup servers that can take over the functions of primary servers that may fail.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Server farms are typically collocated with the network switches and/or routers that enable communication between different parts of the cluster and the cluster's users.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Server "farmers" typically mount computers, routers, power supplies and related electronics on 19-inch racks in a server room or data center.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Server farms are commonly used for cluster computing.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Many modern supercomputers comprise giant server farms of high-speed processors connected by either Ethernet or custom interconnects such as Infiniband or Myrinet.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Web hosting is a common use of a server farm; such a system is sometimes collectively referred to as a *web farm*.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Other uses of server farms include scientific simulations (such as computational fluid dynamics) and the rendering of 3D computer generated imagery (see render farm).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Server farms are increasingly being used instead of or in addition to mainframe computers by large enterprises.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] In large server farms, the failure of an individual machine is a commonplace event: large server farms provide redundancy, automatic failover, and rapid reconfiguration of the server cluster.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] The performance of the largest server farms (thousands of processors and up) is typically limited by the performance of the data center's cooling systems and the total electricity cost rather than by the processors' performance.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Computers in server farms run 24/7 and consume large amounts of electricity.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] For this reason, the critical design parameter for both large and continuous systems tends to be performance per watt rather than cost of peak performance or (peak performance / (unit ⋅ initial cost)).
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] The network connecting the servers in a server farm is also an essential factor in overall performance, especially when running applications that process massive volumes of data.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] The EEMBC EnergyBench, SPECpower, and the Transaction Processing Performance Council TPC-Energy are benchmarks designed to predict performance per watt in a server farm.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] The power used by each rack of equipment can be measured at the power distribution unit.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Some servers include power tracking hardware so the people running the server farm can measure the power used by each server.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] The power used by the entire server farm may be reported in terms of power usage effectiveness or data center infrastructure efficiency.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] According to some estimates, for every 100 watts spent on running the servers, roughly another 50 watts is needed to cool them.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] For this reason, the siting of a server farm can be as important as processor selection in achieving power efficiency.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Iceland, which has a cold climate all year as well as cheap and carbon-neutral geothermal electricity supply, is building its first major server farm hosting site.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Fibre optic cables are being laid from Iceland to North America and Europe to enable companies there to locate their servers in Iceland.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] Other countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden and Switzerland, are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:cloud-load-balancing/server-farm] In these countries, heat from the servers can be cheaply vented or used to help heat buildings, thus reducing the energy consumption of conventional heaters.
